description.text: This will be re-uploaded to another site once a suitible site is found. I do not believe that I, or the original author (in the case of my derived works) appreciates giving up all rights to own our own designs. Once A suitible location is found, or a temporary one is located, A note will be posted here. Have fun! This is a simple adapter for the Losi Mini-8ight for a GoPro camera. Can see it in action here: http://youtu.be/Ehv7GBcJ-Ws It does move the weight up and to the back, making wheelies and rolls a bit easier, but this car is pretty prone to those to begin with, so it's not so bad. Enjoy! ;)

This requires full raft/support to print.  I will probably make a version later that can be printed using soluble material. 
The Losi Mini-8ight has a tail-spoiler that is snapped on with little pins.  Remove the pins, place the wing aside, and put the camera mount on in it's place. (It uses the same pins to secure to the car)

author: robkhristov

description.text:
Mechanical device for extracting toothpaste.
I wanted to create some mechanism with a rachet wheel,and based on a previous toothpaste extractor (think flat thing with slot for toothpaste for winding up the tube) i decided it need some counter rotational mechanism, and what better than the tried and tested ratchet.

Appart from the printet parts, you will need a 3x87mm axle, and a 3x67mm axle. Also a couple of M3x20 bolts (could be M3x25) and accompaying shims and nuts. The parts are printet in red PLa on an ultimaker using netfabb. Ive used standard quailty setting in netfabb for all the parts except for the one ratchet wheel which have been printet using ultra quality. Makes quite a difference, but im sure one can see it on the pictures. The infill spacing is 1.5mm. Th esprings can be adjusted for various stiffness, by altering the infill spacing. Printed parts:
1x10-18-10005 frame
2x10-18-10008 springs
2x10-18-10004 ratchet wheel Assembly
put the long axle through the frame and through the center hole of a ratchet wheel, then put the short axle in the other hole in the ratchet, mount the other ratchet wheel on the two axles, making sure the teeth show the same way, then push the lon axle into the other side of the frame. Mount the springs by drilling holes through the frame and the springs, make sure to mount the them on the right side, like on the pictures, else the ratchet wont work. Have fun :)

title: Y-axis bed stabilizer self tensioning  for Solidoodle 3

description.text:
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://tinkercad.com/things/3cdQ294cnmj
Modified version of stabilizer made by Adoniram

I started with Adoniram's Y axis stabilizer I used his bearing holders then made up a different mount with a tension spring I got at a local hardware store . The rods are 3/16 music wire from local hobby shop 7 inches long with a 90 degree bend at 1 inch from the end . the bearings are 5x11x4 mm as per Adonirams instructions. I did grind to ends of the wire a bit to fit into the bearing holders.Then centered the mount on the bed .You may need to glue the printed parts to the rods but mine are tight enough as printed . Printed at 3mm with support .If you like it let me know .

title: Wheel clips for a GE Dishwasher

description.text:
What can I say... Kids don't have any respect for other peoples property! Since I started making my two girls do the dishes they have destroyed almost all of the wheels on our dishwasher rack! A quick search on Thingiverse found http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:260553
There you can find the wheels and clips. I only needed the clips.
Kudos to chriskorkuch for putting them up there on TV. I printed one, but it didn't turn out that great. Also, the clip is the same style as the ones that break. So, i though I would design my own clips. I think this one is a bit more 3d printer friendly (mine anyway). Also, these push on directly and don't actually clip the way the originals did. Anyway, this worked great for me and I thought I would share. If I spent more time, I could probably make it better. Please let me know if this works for you. Or doesn't. This is my first Thing on TV.

Author printed with ABS. You will need to rotate the model by 90 deg on X. Sorry about that. I wasn't paying attention to that when I modeled it. .2 mm layer height.
50% infill
Printed with support. A bit tough to clean up after print. After print, pop onto wheel. Then push wheel and clip onto the rack till it clicks in place.

description.text:
As an exercise to learn openscad I created a closet rod bracket for my daughters closet.
The funky thing being that one of the walls was on an angle (i.e: not at 90 degrees to the rod).
The scad file has parameters for the various dimensions and for the angle off 90 for the rod support.

The measurements for the .stls are probably not correct for you, so:
  • Measure the size of your hanger rod.
  • Edit the .scad file in OpenScad making the appropriate parameter change
  • Generate the .stl
  • Print
  • Mount in your closet
  • Enjoy keeping your clothes off the ground!

Common standart switch and EU power plug I also put a clip version, but didn't tried it. Look at this OB 1.4 add-ons collection:
http://www.thingiverse.com/Dexerit/collections/ob-14/page:1 Thanks Wired1! Enjoy

Hello people, here is my solution of a spool for loose filament. I have a few samples of filament (20 m per color). so I wanted this to coil and best 3 next to one another. This spool is fully printable and without screws. And can optionally be used with 3 or 4 arms Longer arms here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/make:72957

Printparts:
  • print 3 or 4 arms
  • print 1 "Screw"
  • print 1 "Soket"
    • Screw both elements a little. Set the arms in the long groove.
    Now it gets a little tricky. screw both elements together to further the arms to fix.
    Usually they stick together through friction. If you not trust it, use a dip of Loctite. Hope you got it. Have fun.

I made the angled bevels match the same angle as my tripod head, I made it considerably thinner for faster/cheaper prints. Resized to fit perfectly in my Manfrotto 700RC2 fluid head.
I was at first a bit skeptical of this design; I was concerned that the iPhone could slip out, but it is able to firmly grasp the iPhone even upside-down (see photo).

Print!
I printed at 150mm/s, 50% infill, 0.2mm layers with 0.1mm skin. 
For plastic shrinkage I have my scale set to 103% (thats what I use for all my PLA so far) and it came out the perfect size for my iPhone 4 and Manfrotto.
